header.name: Giordano2020 - SIDARTHE model of COVID-19 spread in Italy
header.description: Giordano2020 - SIDARTHE model of COVID-19 spread in Italy

ModelName.model_summary: The SIDARTHE model simulates the spread of COVID-19 in Italy, focusing on different stages of the disease's progression among the population.

ModelDetails.model_description: The SIDARTHE model is structured around several states representing the progression of COVID-19 among individuals, including Susceptible, Infected, Diagnosed, Ailing, Recognized, Healed, Threatened, and Extinct. Transitions between these states are defined to simulate the spread and impact of the disease. The model is represented in a petrinet format, indicating its suitability for graphical representation of state transitions.

Uses.DirectUse: The model can be used to simulate the spread of COVID-19 in Italy, helping in understanding how the disease progresses through different stages in the population. It can assist in planning and evaluating public health interventions.
Uses.OutOfScopeUse: Using the model to predict the spread of diseases other than COVID-19, or in regions with significantly different demographics or health systems than Italy, may be inappropriate and lead to misleading conclusions.

BiasRisksLimitations.bias_risks_limitations: The model's accuracy is dependent on the quality and representativeness of the input data. Biases in data collection or assumptions made in the model's structure may lead to inaccuracies in predictions. Additionally, the model's focus on Italy may limit its applicability to other contexts without adjustments.

Evaluation.TestingDataFactorsMetrics: The model's validation details are not provided in the configuration. Typically, such models are validated through comparison with real-world data, sensitivity analysis, and simulation studies to assess their accuracy and robustness.

TechnicalSpecifications.model_specs: The model includes a detailed set of states and transitions, with parameters defined for each transition. It operates on a continuous time basis, with differential equations governing the rates of transition between states.

model_parameters: The model parameters include transmission rates (beta, gamma, delta, alpha), diagnosis rates (epsilon, eta), recovery rates (rho, theta, kappa, xi, lambda), and mortality rates (mu, tau, sigma).
